          "body": "Boaz's blessing in 2:12 is the chapter's theological peak: 'May your wages be full from the LORD, the God of Israel, under whose wings you have come to seek refuge.' The word for wings is kanaph — the same word Ruth will use in 3:9 when she asks Boaz to spread his own kanaph over her. The progression is deliberate. Boaz prays that the LORD will reward Ruth from His wings; in chapter 3, Ruth asks Boaz to be the instrument of that very wing. The wings-of-God image draws on Psalm 17:8, 36:7, 57:1, 91:4 — Israel's God as a sheltering bird (compare Deuteronomy 32:11, the eagle who bears her young). That this refuge is now available to a Moabite woman is not incidental to the book's theology; it is central. Ruth is the Gentile inclusion in the covenant story, four generations before David, grafted into the line through which the Messiah will come (Matthew 1:5)."
