          "body": "Naomi's bitter complaint in 1:20-21 — 'Do not call me Naomi; call me Mara... I went out full but the LORD has brought me back empty' — is the darkness against which chapter 2 lights a candle. Ruth returns from the field carrying approximately thirty pounds of barley (an ephah, roughly what a male worker might earn in several days) and the surplus food from Boaz's own table (2:18). She gives Naomi both. The emptiness of 1:21 is not resolved all at once; this is the first installment. But the trajectory has reversed. The LORD who apparently brought Naomi back empty (1:21) has begun filling her through a Moabite daughter-in-law and a kinsman whose name she recognizes. D. A. Carson notes in his commentary on Ruth that the book's structure is carefully chiastic: the lowest point of the book (1:20-21) is immediately followed by the first signs of reversal (the harvest-timing note of 1:22, then the encounter of chapter 2). Providence does not wait for Naomi's bitterness to resolve before it begins acting."
