          "body": "The book of Ruth does not allow the reader to stay safely inside the covenant people looking out. Its heroine is a Moabite — a member of a nation whose origins are incestuous (Genesis 19:37), who hired Balaam against Israel (Numbers 22), and who were excluded from the assembly of Israel to the tenth generation (Deuteronomy 23:3). Yet Ruth's loyalty to Naomi (described in 1:14-18) is the human act that sets everything in motion, and Boaz names it explicitly: 'all that you have done for your mother-in-law... how you left your father and your mother and the land of your birth, and came to a people that you did not previously know' (2:11). Boaz hears in Ruth's biography an echo of Abraham — the same language of leaving family and homeland to go to a people not previously known (Genesis 12:1). Ruth is, in Boaz's estimation, a genuine proselyte whose chesed to Naomi demonstrates she has genuinely come under the wings of the God of Israel. The New Testament will make this logic explicit: genuine faith is ethnically unrestricted (Galatians 3:28; Romans 4:11-12), and Ruth's inclusion in the Davidic genealogy (Matthew 1:5) is the Old Testament's anticipation of it."
