        "body": "The narrator introduces Boaz in verse 1 before Ruth ever meets him. This is a literary technique that functions theologically: the reader knows what Ruth does not — that the man she will encounter is already named, already identified as Elimelech's kinsman, already described as a man of great wealth and noble character. Ruth enters the field without this knowledge. The narrator arranges the scene so that the reader watches providence operate invisibly from Ruth's perspective.\n\nVerse 3 contains the book's most theologically loaded phrase: wayiqer miqrehah — literally, 'and her chance chanced upon her.' The Hebrew root qarah means 'to happen, to meet by chance,' and the narrator uses both the verb and the related noun in a single clause. Most translations flatten this to 'she happened to come' (NASB) or 'as it turned out' (NIV). But the doubled root is deliberate — the author is not unaware that he is using chance language. He is using it precisely because the surface appearance of the event is coincidence, and he wants the reader to feel the gap between appearance and reality.\n\nBoaz arrives from Bethlehem at 2:4, apparently at the moment Ruth has already begun gleaning. He notices her immediately — 'Whose young woman is this?' (2:5). His foreman knows Ruth's story. Boaz has been fully briefed before he speaks a word to her (2:11 — 'all that you have done... has been fully reported to me'). The layers of preparation are the narrator's portrait of providence: God does not parachute Boaz in at the last moment. He has arranged the information flow, the timing, the family connections, and the harvest calendar so that the right woman meets the right man on the right day in the right field.\n\nFor the student of biblical theology, this verse is the hermeneutical key to the whole book. Ruth is not a story about luck improving. It is a story about the God who governs history through the texture of ordinary days — who is present and active precisely where He seems most absent. The same theology undergirds Joseph's narrative ('you meant it for evil; God meant it for good,' Genesis 50:20), Esther's story, and ultimately the incarnation itself — God arriving in the most ordinary human form at the most unexpected moment.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Wayiqer miqrehah* — the doubled root *qarah* (chance/happen) is the narrator's ironic signal. *Gibbor chayil* (2:1 — 'man of great wealth,' NASB; or 'prominent man of noble character') combines military valor (*gibbor*) with social/moral excellence (*chayil*). The same phrase describes Gideon (Judges 6:12) and David's mighty men (1 Chronicles 12:25). Boaz is no ordinary landowner."
