        "excerpt": "Do not go to glean in another field; furthermore, do not go on from this one, but stay here with my maids… I have commanded the servants not to touch you.",
        "body": "Boaz's opening greeting to his workers (2:4 — 'May the LORD be with you' / 'May the LORD bless you') is not incidental local color. It establishes the theological register of his household. This is a man whose workplace runs on Yahweh's name. The Mosaic gleaning law (Leviticus 19:9-10; Deuteronomy 24:19-22) is the backdrop, but Boaz's conduct goes far beyond what the law requires. He does not merely leave corners and fallen grain; he gives Ruth permission to drink from his workers' supply (2:9), seats her at his own table at mealtime (2:14), serves her personally (2:14), commands his workers to let her glean among the sheaves themselves (2:15 — the area normally reserved for the hired workforce, not gleaning outsiders), and then commands them to pull grain from the bundled sheaves and drop it intentionally for her to find (2:16). This last command is the most remarkable: it is secret generosity, invisible to Ruth. She will think she gleaned it herself.\n\nBoaz's explanation for his generosity (2:11-12) is critical for interpretation. He does not appeal to the gleaning law or to pity. He appeals to Ruth's track record: 'All that you have done for your mother-in-law after the death of your husband has been fully reported to me.' He names three specific sacrifices: she left her father, her mother, and her homeland. The verbal parallel to Abraham's call in Genesis 12:1 ('Go from your country and your kindred and your father's house') is likely intentional — the same three elements of departure in the same order. Boaz is identifying Ruth as a person who has responded to the covenant God with the kind of trust Abraham modeled. His generosity flows from theological recognition, not mere humanitarian instinct.\n\nThe meal scene in 2:14 deserves extended attention. Boaz says, 'Come here, that you may eat of the bread and dip your piece of bread in the vinegar.' Then 'he served her roasted grain, and she ate and was satisfied and had some left.' The language of eating, satisfaction, and abundance (sava — 'was satisfied' — the same root as shalem, wholeness/completeness) echoes Israel's covenant promises in Deuteronomy 8:10-12 and anticipates the messianic banquet of Isaiah 25:6-9. Ruth the outsider is not merely given a crust; she is fed to satisfaction and has leftovers. This is a table scene, and in the Old Testament table scenes carry covenantal weight: Melchizedek's bread and wine (Genesis 14:18), the meal on Sinai (Exodus 24:11), the Passover table. Boaz's table is not quite those, but the narrator's language reaches in that direction.\n\nThe student of biblical theology should press the typological question: if Boaz embodies chesed toward a Moabite outcast — going beyond law, providing food and protection, covering shame with generosity — what does this say about the One whom Boaz prefigures? Calvin saw it plainly: the go'el-redeemer of Ruth is a type of Christ, not because the book explicitly says so, but because the pattern of redemption it narrates — kinsman, obligation, voluntary excess, table inclusion of the outsider — recurs in the New Testament's portrait of the Redeemer who 'though He was rich, yet for your sake He became poor' (2 Corinthians 8:9).\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Chesed* (2:20) is the chapter's interpretive capstone, but Boaz enacts it throughout without using the word. *Sava* (2:14, 'was satisfied') is the same root as *shalem* (wholeness) and *shalom* — satisfaction, completeness, peace. *Laqat* (to glean) occurs nine times in the chapter; its saturation keeps the reader anchored in Ruth's social vulnerability, against which Boaz's excess becomes the more striking."
