        "excerpt": "Why have I found favor in your sight that you should take notice of me, since I am a foreigner?",
        "body": "Ruth's response to Boaz's provision is the theological counterpoint to his generosity. She falls on her face (2:10) — the posture of worship, the same verb (*shachah*) used for bowing before God or a king. Her question is genuine: she cannot explain why this man would take notice of a nokhriah, a foreigner. The word nokhriah is sharper than ger (resident alien); it denotes someone from outside the covenant entirely, a genuine outsider without inherited claim on Israelite covenant mercy.\n\nHer second statement (2:13) is equally striking: 'I have found favor in your sight, my lord, for you have comforted me and indeed have spoken kindly to your maidservant, though I am not like one of your maidservants.' She does not claim the status she is being given. She receives grace without renegotiating her position. 'I am not like one of your maidservants' — the maidservants (shiphchot) were Israelite women with covenant standing and a social position within Boaz's household. Ruth explicitly disclaims equivalence. She accepts the grace while maintaining clarity about where she actually stands.\n\nThis posture is the New Testament's posture before God. The tax collector of Luke 18:13 ('God, be merciful to me, the sinner') and the prodigal's younger son ('I am no longer worthy to be called your son,' Luke 15:19) both receive more than they asked for precisely because they did not negotiate upward from their starting position. Grace is received, not leveraged. Peter Davids, commenting on the New Testament's use of the Ruth narrative's themes, notes that the posture of the one who comes to the covenant God with nothing — no lineage, no status, no merit — and receives everything is the paradigmatic posture of faith in both Testaments.\n\nRuth's behavior also illuminates her chesed. The word chesed (2:20) will be applied by Naomi to describe Boaz's treatment of her household, but Ruth has already enacted chesed toward Naomi in chapter 1 (the oath of 1:16-17). In 2:18, after being satisfied herself, she takes back to Naomi the leftover food from the meal. She could have eaten it herself; she had worked for it. Instead, she shares the excess. The outsider who has received more than she deserved immediately becomes a conduit of that excess to someone else. This is the logic of grace: it does not stop with the recipient."
