        "excerpt": "May he be blessed of the Lord who has not withdrawn his kindness to the living and to the dead.",
        "body": "Naomi's exclamation in 2:20 is the chapter's interpretive peak. When Ruth reports that the man's name is Boaz, Naomi responds with a blessing: 'May he be blessed of the LORD who has not withdrawn his kindness (*chesed*) to the living and to the dead.' The pronoun 'who' (*asher*) is grammatically ambiguous — its antecedent could be Boaz or the LORD. Most commentators (Hubbard, Campbell, Block) argue for intentional ambiguity: the blessing names Boaz, but the chesed that has not been withdrawn belongs ultimately to Yahweh. Boaz is the instrument; the LORD is the source. This is the book's theology in a single sentence.\n\nThe phrase 'the living and the dead' is striking. The living are Naomi and Ruth — both widows with immediate physical needs. The dead are Elimelech and Mahlon and Chilion (named in 1:3-5) — the men whose deaths left the women destitute. Naomi is saying that Yahweh's covenant loyalty extends across death. The go'el system is explicitly designed for this: the kinsman-redeemer acts on behalf of the dead man's estate and name, not merely the living widow. Boaz's provision reaches backward, as it were, to honor men who are gone — which is why the book culminates not in a love story but in the birth of a son who is given to Naomi (4:17) to restore the name and line of Elimelech.\n\nNaomi then adds the operative identification: 'The man is our relative — he is one of our go'elim.' This is the chapter's plot-turning disclosure. Everything in chapters 3-4 depends on it. Naomi moves from bitter resignation (1:20-21 — the LORD has dealt bitterly with me) to active wisdom (2:22 — it is good that you go with his maids; 3:1ff — my daughter, shall I not seek security for you?). Her theology has not changed — she always believed in Yahweh. What has changed is her perception of what He is doing. Chapter 2 is the chapter where Naomi's emptiness begins to acquire meaning.\n\nFor canonical context: the go'el institution in Ruth points forward to the New Testament's kinsman-redeemer Christology in ways that must not be allegorized too quickly but also must not be suppressed. Hebrews 2:14-17 uses exactly this logic: 'Since the children share in flesh and blood, He Himself likewise also partook of the same... Therefore He had to be made like His brethren in all things, so that He might become a merciful and faithful high priest.' The Son became kin — took on our nature — so that He could legally and covenantally act as our go'el. The incarnation is the ultimate kinsman-redeemer move.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Chesed* is notoriously difficult to translate — NASB uses 'kindness,' ESV 'steadfast love,' KJV 'lovingkindness.' The word combines loyalty (covenant obligation), love (genuine affection), and excess (going beyond what is required). It is the word used in Exodus 34:6-7 for Yahweh's own character. When it appears in Ruth 2:20, the reader is meant to feel the weight of the entire divine character behind Boaz's actions. *Gaal* (go'el, kinsman-redeemer, 2:20) is the same root used in Job 19:25 ('I know that my Redeemer lives') and Isaiah 43:14 ('your Redeemer, the Holy One of Israel')."
