        "body": "Verse 23 compresses two months into two clauses and functions as a narrative bridge. Ruth obeys Naomi's counsel (2:22 — go out with his maids) and stays close to Boaz's workforce through the entire harvest season, from barley (late April) through wheat (early June). The verb davaq — to cling, to stay close — is the same verb used of Ruth's attachment to Naomi in 1:14. The quality of loyalty that Ruth showed Naomi, she now shows in obedient proximity to Boaz's household. The word unifies the book's moral portrait of its heroine.\n\nThe final clause — 'and she lived with her mother-in-law' — is a quiet but pointed statement. After the harvest ends, Ruth does not set up her own household or seek another benefactor. She returns to Naomi. The two women are still a unit. The provision of chapter 2 has not dissolved their bond; it has strengthened it. Naomi's counsel in chapter 3 ('shall I not seek security for you?') flows naturally from this continued living-together: the older woman is still thinking about the younger one's future.\n\nThe harvest's end creates the narrative pressure of chapter 3. While the harvest was active, Ruth had access to Boaz's field, his table, and his workers' company. When the harvest ends, all of that ends. The question the chapter leaves hanging is: what now? Naomi's answer in 3:1-4 is to press the go'el claim. The legal identification of 2:20 must now be activated. The book has been moving toward this moment since 2:1; the harvest summary is the last breath before the plunge.\n\nFor the student reading Ruth canonically: the book is deliberately positioned between Judges (chaos, moral failure, covenant unfaithfulness) and 1 Samuel (the rise of kingship). It offers a small-scale portrait of covenant faithfulness working at the ground level — two widows, a harvest, a kinsman — that will culminate in David's genealogy (4:17-22). The great providential movements of redemptive history (the Davidic covenant, the messianic hope) rest on small acts of chesed like the ones Ruth 2 narrates. God builds His kingdom through the ordinary faithfulness of ordinary people in ordinary harvests."
